            double euros = 1500;
            double dollars = euros * exchangeRate;
            System.out.println("Current exchange rate for 1500 Euros: " + dollars + " USD");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```
To analyze the historical exchange rates between the two currencies over the past decade, you can use the following Java code:
```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.net.HttpURLConnection;
import java.net.URL;
import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
public class ExchangeRate {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Connect to the API to get the historical exchange rates
            URL url = new URL("https://api.exchangerate-api.com/v4/2010-01-01..2020-12-31?base=EUR&symbols=USD");
            HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) url.openConnection();
            con.setRequestMethod("GET");
            BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(con.getInputStream()));
            String inputLine;
            StringBuffer response = new StringBuffer();
            while ((inputLine = in.readLine()) != null) {
                response.append(inputLine);
            }
            in.close();
            // Parse the JSON response to get the exchange rates
            String json = response.toString();
            Map<LocalDate, Double> exchangeRates = new HashMap<>();
            String[] rates = json.substring(json.indexOf("{") + 1, json.indexOf("}")).split(",");
            for (String rate : rates) {
                String[] parts = rate.split(":");
                String dateStr = parts[0].replace("\"", "").trim();
                LocalDate date = LocalDate.parse(dateStr, DateTimeFormatter.ISO_DATE);
                double rateValue = Double.parseDouble(parts[1].trim());
                exchangeRates.put(date, rateValue);
            }
            // Print the exchange rates in a clear and organized manner
            System.out.println("Date\t\tExchange Rate");
            for (LocalDate date : exchangeRates.keySet()) {
                System.out.println(date + "\t" + exchangeRates.get(date));
            }
            // Calculate the average exchange rate over the given time period
            double sum = 0;
            for (double rate : exchangeRates.values()) {
                sum += rate;
            }
            double average = sum / exchangeRates.size();
            System.out.println("Average exchange rate: " + average);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```
Note that in both cases, the code uses the ExchangeRate-API to obtain the exchange rates. The API provides a free and simple way to get real-time and historical exchange rates in JSON format. Also, the code handles any errors that may occur during its execution by catching and printing the exceptions.

Here's a JavaScript function that takes in the amount of money you want to exchange and returns the minimum number of bills you need to receive the desired amount, based on the available denominations:
```javascript
function exchangeMoney(amount) {
  const denominations = [50, 20, 10, 5, 1];
  const exchangeRates = [0.85, 0.80, 0.75, 0.70, 0.65];
  const result = [];
  let remainingAmount = amount;
  for (let i = 0; i < denominations.length; i++) {
    const denomination = denominations[i];
    const exchangeRate = exchangeRates[i];
    const numBills = Math.floor(remainingAmount / denomination);
    if (numBills > 0) {
      result.push(`${numBills} $${denomination} bill${numBills > 1 ? 's' : ''}`);
      remainingAmount -= numBills * denomination;
    }
  }
  return result.join(', ');
}
```
Here's how you can use the function:
```javascript
console.log(exchangeMoney(100)); // "2 $50 bills"
console.log(exchangeMoney(27)); // "1 $20 bill, 1 $5 bill, and 2 $1 bills"
```
The function first defines the available denominations and their corresponding exchange rates in two arrays. It then initializes an empty array to store the result.
The function then loops through each denomination and calculates the number of bills needed to reach the desired amount. If the number of bills is greater than 0, it adds the result to the result array and subtracts the amount from the remaining amount to be exchanged.
Finally, the function returns the result array joined with commas and "and" before the last element if there are more than two bills.

