To analyze the changes in dynamics of a piano piece, you can use MATLAB to calculate the Root Mean Square (RMS) values of the audio signal over time. The RMS values represent the average power of the audio signal and can be used to determine the fluctuations in volume.
Here is an example code using the piano piece you provided:
```matlab
% Load audio file
[y, Fs] = audioread('piano_piece.mp3');
% Convert stereo audio to mono
if size(y, 2) == 2
    y = mean(y, 2);
end
% Define parameters
winSize = 0.1; % Window size in seconds
hopSize = 0.05; % Hop size in seconds
key = 'C'; % Key of the piano piece
tempo = 120; % Tempo of the piano piece
% Convert key to frequency
keyFreq = note2freq(key);
% Convert tempo to beats per minute (BPM)
BPM = tempo;
% Calculate beat duration in seconds
beatDuration = 60 / BPM;
% Calculate frame size and hop size in samples
winSizeSamples = round(winSize * Fs);
hopSizeSamples = round(hopSize * Fs);
% Calculate number of frames
numFrames = floor((length(y) - winSizeSamples) / hopSizeSamples) + 1;
% Initialize RMS values and time stamps
RMS = zeros(numFrames, 1);
timeStamps = zeros(numFrames, 1);
% Calculate RMS values and time stamps for each frame
for i = 1:numFrames
    % Calculate start and end samples of the frame
    startSample = (i - 1) * hopSizeSamples + 1;
    endSample = startSample + winSizeSamples - 1;

    % Calculate RMS value of the frame
    RMS(i) = sqrt(mean(y(startSample:endSample).^2));

    % Calculate time stamp of the frame
    timeStamps(i) = (startSample + endSample) / 2 / Fs;
end
% Plot RMS values over time
figure;
plot(timeStamps, RMS);
xlabel('Time (s)');
ylabel('RMS');
title('RMS values over time');
% Find notes and sections of the piano piece
notes = {'C', 'D', 'E', 'F', 'G', 'A', 'B'};
sections = {'Intro', 'Verse 1', 'Chorus', 'Verse 2', 'Chorus', 'Bridge', 'Chorus', 'Outro'};
noteStarts = [0, 0.5, 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3];
sectionStarts = [0, 10, 25, 40, 55, 70, 85, 100];
noteDurations = [0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 1];
sectionDurations = [10, 15, 15, 15, 15, 15, 15, 10];
% Calculate note and section RMS values
noteRMS = zeros(length(notes), 1);
sectionRMS = zeros(length(sections), 1);
for i = 1:length(notes)
    noteFreq = note2freq(notes{i});
    noteRMS(i) = mean(RMS(abs(keyFreq - noteFreq) < 10));
end
for i = 1:length(sections)
    sectionStart = sectionStarts(i);
    sectionEnd = sectionStart + sectionDurations(i);
    sectionRMS(i) = mean(RMS(timeStamps >= sectionStart & timeStamps < sectionEnd));
end
% Plot note and section RMS values
figure;
subplot(2, 1, 1);
bar(noteRMS);
set(gca, 'XTick', 1:length(notes), 'XTickLabel', notes);
xlabel('Note');
ylabel('RMS');
title('Note RMS values');
subplot(2, 1, 2);
bar(sectionRMS);
set(gca, 'XTick', 1:length(sections), 'XTickLabel', sections);
xlabel('Section');
ylabel('RMS');
title('Section RMS values');
```
In this code, we first load the audio file and convert it to mono if it is stereo. We then define the parameters for the analysis, including the window size, hop size, key, and tempo. We calculate the beat duration based on the tempo and convert the frame size and hop size to samples. We then calculate the RMS values and time stamps for each frame using a for loop. We plot the RMS values over time to visualize the changes in dynamics.
We also define the notes and sections of the piano piece and calculate the RMS values for each note and section. We use the `note2freq` function to convert the note names to frequencies. We then plot the note and section RMS values to visualize how the fluctuations in volume relate to specific notes and sections.
Note that the `note2freq` function is not built-in to MATLAB, so you will need to define it yourself. Here is an example implementation:
```matlab
function freq = note2freq(note)
% Converts a note name to a frequency in Hz
% Example: note2freq('A#4') returns 466.16 Hz
A4 = 440; % Frequency of A4 in Hz
notes = {'C', 'C#', 'D', 'D#', 'E', 'F', 'F#', 'G', 'G#', 'A', 'A#', 'B'};
noteNum = str2double(note(2:end));
noteName = note(1);
if length(note) == 3
    noteName = [noteName, note(3)];
end
noteIdx = find(strcmp(notes, noteName));
freq = A4 * 2^((noteNum - 4) + (noteIdx - 10) / 12);
end
```
This function takes a note name as input (e.g., 'A#4') and returns the corresponding frequency in Hz.

