What are the key changes implemented by the 2009 amendments to the U.S. tobacco legislation, and how have these efforts impacted the tobacco industry?
\section{Background}
In 2009, the United States Congress passed the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act (FSPTCA), which amended the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act to give the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) the authority to regulate tobacco products. The FSPTCA aimed to reduce the number of Americans who smoke and to prevent minors from accessing tobacco products.
\section{Key Changes}
The 2009 amendments to the U.S. tobacco legislation included several key changes:
\begin{itemize}
  \item FDA Regulation: The FDA gained the authority to regulate the manufacturing, marketing, and distribution of tobacco products, and was empowered to set standards for tobacco product content, labeling, and advertising.
  \item Warning Labels: Tobacco products were required to include new graphic warning labels that covered at least 50% of the front and back of cigarette packages.
  \item Flavored Tobacco Products: The sale of flavored cigarettes (with the exception of menthol) was banned, and the FDA was given the authority to regulate flavored tobacco products.
  \item Marketing to Minors: The sale of cigarettes and smokeless tobacco to minors was prohibited, and tobacco companies were prohibited from sponsoring youth-oriented events.
\end{itemize}
\section{Impact on Tobacco Industry}
The 2009 amendments to the U.S. tobacco legislation had a significant impact on the tobacco industry. Tobacco companies were required to comply with new regulations and standards, and were subject to increased scrutiny from the FDA. The new warning labels and restrictions on marketing to minors also impacted the way tobacco products were sold and advertised. Some tobacco companies challenged the constitutionality of the FSPTCA, but the U.S. Supreme Court ultimately upheld the law in 2012. Despite these efforts, tobacco use remains a significant public health issue in the United States, and the FDA continues to work towards reducing tobacco use and preventing minors from accessing tobacco products.

