How can I perform emotion classification in R based on a pre-existing list of emotions and their corresponding numerical values? The list must include at least 10 different emotions with values ranging from -50 to 50. 
Here is an example code that can be modified to use this list for classification:
emotions <- c("joy", "anger", "sadness", "fear", "surprise", "disgust", "love", "hope", "envy", "pride")
values <- c(40, -30, -45, -20, 25, -35, 50, 30, -15, 20)
text <- "This is a sample text for emotion classification."
# calculate the emotion score based on pre-existing list
score <- 0
for(i in 1:length(emotions)) {
  emotion <- emotions[i]
  value <- values[i]
  score <- score + (length(grep(emotion, text, ignore.case = TRUE)) * value)
}
# classify the emotion based on score
if(score >= 50) {
  classification <- "very positive"
} else if(score >= 20) {
  classification <- "positive"
} else if(score >= -20) {
  classification <- "neutral"
} else if(score >= -50) {
  classification <- "negative"
} else {
  classification <- "very negative"
}
print(paste("The text is classified as", classification, "with a score of", score))

