How can I modify this R function to generate sentences with the "Too big for one’s boots" idiom only when the subject is plural? I have a list of possible plural subjects and objects in an Excel table that I would like to use to create a variety of sentences. Additionally, can the function output the meaning of the idiom as defined in a [language dictionary] data format, and the connotation of the idiom in the context of the generated sentence? 
Here is the Excel table with the possible plural subjects and objects:
| Plural Subjects | Plural Objects |
|----------------|----------------|
| cats           | hats           |
| dogs           | logs           |
| horses         | courses        |
| cars           | bars           |
And here is the code for the R function:
```
generate_sentence <- function(subjects, objects) {
  idiom <- "Too big for one's boots"
  subject <- sample(subjects, 1)
  object <- sample(objects, 1)
  if (subject == "I") {
    verb <- "am"
  } else {
    verb <- "are"
  }
  sentence <- paste(subject, verb, idiom, "about", object)
  return(sentence)
}
```

