When faced with limited access to testing resources, a software development team can employ the following strategies to ensure quality assurance:
1. Prioritizing testing: The team should prioritize the most critical areas of the application and focus their testing efforts on those areas.
2. Test automation: The team can leverage test automation tools to reduce the manual effort required for testing. This can help them to test more areas of the application in less time.
3. Risk-based testing: The team can identify the areas of the application that are most critical to the business and focus their testing efforts on those areas.
4. Exploratory testing: The team can use exploratory testing to identify defects that may not be caught by automated or manual testing.
In Java, there are several innovative approaches that can be used to incorporate automated testing into the development process. Some of these approaches include:
1. Behavior-driven development (BDD): BDD is a development approach that uses natural language to describe the behavior of an application. This approach can help to ensure that the application meets the requirements of the business.
2. Test-driven development (TDD): TDD is a development approach that requires developers to write automated tests before writing the code. This approach can help to ensure that the code meets the requirements of the business.
3. Continuous integration and testing: Continuous integration and testing is an approach that involves integrating code changes into a shared repository on a regular basis and running automated tests to ensure that the changes do not break the application.
Here is an example of how to implement integration testing using Selenium WebDriver in Java:
```java
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.testng.Assert;
import org.testng.annotations.AfterClass;
import org.testng.annotations.BeforeClass;
import org.testng.annotations.Test;
public class IntegrationTest {
    private WebDriver driver;
    @BeforeClass
    public void setUp() {
        System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver", "path/to/chromedriver.exe");
        driver = new ChromeDriver();
    }
    @AfterClass
    public void tearDown() {
        driver.quit();
    }
    @Test
    public void testIntegration() {
        driver.get("https://www.example.com");
        String title = driver.getTitle();
        Assert.assertEquals(title, "Example Domain");
    }
}
```
In this example, we are using Selenium WebDriver to test the integration between our application and the Example Domain website. We are verifying that the title of the page is "Example Domain". The `setUp()` method is used to set up the Selenium WebDriver and the `tearDown()` method is used to close the browser after the test is complete. The `@Test` annotation is used to indicate that this is a test method. The `Assert.assertEquals()` method is used to compare the actual title of the page with the expected title. If the actual title does not match the expected title, the test will fail.
